On one hand, I identify as an extrovert -- this past summer, the majority of my time I spent hanging out with friends and exploring SF, nearly spending entire days surrounded by other people. I also would say that my loneliest times at Cal are when I've been at home while no one else is -- I hate the feeling of FOMO, and more than that, I think the majority of the joy I gain from daily life is talking to others. This summer, I specifically made the trip into my office (~25 min walk) just so that I could see others and enjoy spontaneous points of interaction, be that at the Cafe, at my desk, or somewhere in between. I love planning trips with friends and also love to go on spontaneous adventures as well.

On the other hand, I can definitely be very introverted/antisocial at times. Most of my fall 2020 semester I spent alone, with just my mom for company as we waited out quarantine in our Santa Cruz residence. I had a great time embracing solitude and finding joy in the little moments, like finishing a good hike or taking a quick jog in the morning. I also love cafes and libraries, and most of my hobbies are individual tasks (reading, painting, drawing, walks, etc.). I would say that I am a very reflective person, and I spend a good deal of my time alone thinking about my values and goals, and meditating on them. 

I would say in terms of my feelings, that I feel deeply. If I'm happy, I've been known to be the center of the party -- I love to pull people into my happiness bubble, and to share the joy that I'm feeling with my friends, family, and even strangers. If I'm sad, I feel sad deeply as well -- I cry at least 1-2 times a semester because of difficulties that I'm facing, and I also see embracing sorrow as a healthy way of recalibrating my emotions. Given that, I think that my feelings can be relatively volatile at times, especially since I think that I vary between strong moods (ex. being really sad/happy for a while) or intense emotions that pass surprisingly quickly (ex. I was really sad on Saturday that the summer was over, but now, a few days later, I feel as if that was a long time ago and a very different person at that).
negative_text:
I would say the first thing that comes to mind is the fact that I am a very empathetic person, which I can at times use for manipulative reasons. I would hate to think of myself as very cunning/"snake-y", but at the same time I've been known to plan out my responses to certain situations in full awareness of how that would manipulate the actions of those around me. 

I think I also can be a bad friend, when it comes to flexing my other friendships and being really busy. For example, I've made it no secret that I made a really close group of friends this summer, and I think that sometimes when I talk to my Berkeley friends they feel as if I've already moved on as a person. 

Finally, I think that try as I would like, I still get jealous easily and wish that parts of my life were different. It makes me sad/envious that most of my good friends are now in relationships, and at times I wonder why I couldn't be like them too. I also feel jealous when it comes to the number of friends people have, or how spread out they are (most of my friends are in CA), or other social aspects like that.
